episode_body:
Title: Migration: FiberRef.get replaced by yielding Reference directly
Category: migration
Source: fiberref.md

Change: Reading fiber-local state changed from FiberRef.get(ref) to yielding the Reference directly via yield*.

v3 Pattern:
import { Effect, FiberRef } from "effect"
const program = Effect.gen(function*() {
  const level = yield* FiberRef.get(FiberRef.currentLogLevel)
})

v4 Pattern:
import { Effect, References } from "effect"
const program = Effect.gen(function*() {
  const level = yield* References.CurrentLogLevel // "Info" (default)
})

Reason: References are services - you yield* them directly like any other service, no special get function needed.

Affected Modules: FiberRef (removed), References

Title: Migration: FiberRef.set replaced by Effect.provideService scoping
Category: migration
Source: fiberref.md

Change: FiberRef.set for mutating fiber-local state replaced by Effect.provideService which scopes the value to the provided effect.

v3 Pattern:
import { Effect, FiberRef } from "effect"
const program = Effect.gen(function*() {
  yield* FiberRef.set(FiberRef.currentConcurrency, 10)
  // subsequent code sees concurrency = 10
})

v4 Pattern:
import { Effect, References } from "effect"
const program = Effect.provideService(
  Effect.gen(function*() {
    const concurrency = yield* References.CurrentConcurrency
    console.log(concurrency) // 10
  }),
  References.CurrentConcurrency,
  10
)

Reason: There is no mutable set operation. References are scoped via Effect.provideService, making the scope of the value explicit.

Affected Modules: Effect, References

Title: Migration: Layer memoization now shared across Effect.provide calls
Category: migration
Source: layer-memoization.md

Change: In v3, each Effect.provide call had its own memoization scope, so overlapping layers would be built multiple times. In v4, the MemoMap is shared between Effect.provide calls by default, so layers are automatically deduplicated.

v3 Pattern:
const main = program.pipe(
  Effect.provide(MyServiceLayer),
  Effect.provide(MyServiceLayer)
)
// v3: "Building MyService" logged TWICE - each provide has its own memo map

v4 Pattern:
const main = program.pipe(
  Effect.provide(MyServiceLayer),
  Effect.provide(MyServiceLayer)
)
// v4: "Building MyService" logged ONCE - shared memo map deduplicates

Reason: Prevents accidental double-building of layers when using multiple Effect.provide calls. This was a common footgun in v3.

Affected Modules: Layer, Effect

Title: Migration: Context.Tag class syntax replaced by ServiceMap.Service class syntax
Category: migration
Source: services.md

Change: Class-based service definition syntax changed. In v3, the identifier string was passed to Context.Tag(id) before type parameters. In v4, type parameters come first via ServiceMap.Service<Self, Shape>() and the identifier is passed to the returned constructor.

v3 Pattern:
import { Context } from "effect"
class Database extends Context.Tag("Database")<Database, {
  readonly query: (sql: string) => string
}>() {}

v4 Pattern:
import { ServiceMap } from "effect"
class Database extends ServiceMap.Service<Database, {
  readonly query: (sql: string) => string
}>()("Database") {}

Reason: Changed argument order - type parameters first, then identifier. This enables better type inference.

Affected Modules: Context (removed), ServiceMap

Title: Migration: Effect.Tag accessors removed, replaced by Service.use and Service.useSync
Category: migration
Source: services.md

Change: v3's Effect.Tag provided proxy access to service methods as static properties (accessors). This is removed in v4. Use Service.use or Service.useSync instead, or prefer yield* in generators.

v3 Pattern:
class Notifications extends Effect.Tag("Notifications")<Notifications, {
  readonly notify: (message: string) => Effect.Effect<void>
}>() {}
// Static proxy access
const program = Notifications.notify("hello")

v4 Pattern:
class Notifications extends ServiceMap.Service<Notifications, {
  readonly notify: (message: string) => Effect.Effect<void>
}>()("Notifications") {}
// use: access the service and call a method in one step
const program = Notifications.use((n) => n.notify("hello"))
// useSync: for pure/synchronous accessors
const port = Config.useSync((c) => c.port)
// Preferred: yield* in generators
const program2 = Effect.gen(function*() {
  const notifications = yield* Notifications
  yield* notifications.notify("hello")
})

Reason: The proxy approach lost generic type parameters and overloaded signatures. Service.use makes the conversion explicit. yield* is preferred for most cases.

Affected Modules: Effect (Effect.Tag removed), ServiceMap

Title: Migration: Effect.Service replaced by ServiceMap.Service with make option
Category: migration
Source: services.md

Change: v3's Effect.Service with effect/dependencies options replaced by ServiceMap.Service with make option. v4 does NOT auto-generate a .Default layer - you must build layers explicitly.

v3 Pattern:
class Logger extends Effect.Service<Logger>()("Logger", {
  effect: Effect.gen(function*() {
    const config = yield* Config
    return { log: (msg: string) => Effect.log(`[${config.prefix}] ${msg}`) }
  }),
  dependencies: [Config.Default]
}) {}
// Logger.Default is auto-generated: Layer<Logger, never, never>
program.pipe(Effect.provide(Logger.Default))

v4 Pattern:
class Logger extends ServiceMap.Service<Logger>()("Logger", {
  make: Effect.gen(function*() {
    const config = yield* Config
    return { log: (msg: string) => Effect.log(`[${config.prefix}] ${msg}`) }
  })
}) {
  static layer = Layer.effect(this, this.make).pipe(Layer.provide(Config.layer))
}
// Build layer yourself, wire dependencies via Layer.provide
// Convention: use .layer instead of .Default or .Live

Reason: Explicit layer construction makes the dependency graph visible. The dependencies option is removed. v4 convention is .layer instead of .Default/.Live.

Affected Modules: Effect (Effect.Service removed), ServiceMap, Layer

Title: Migration: Context.Reference replaced by ServiceMap.Reference
Category: migration
Source: services.md

Change: Context.Reference class-based syntax replaced by ServiceMap.Reference function syntax.

v3 Pattern:
import { Context } from "effect"
class LogLevel extends Context.Reference<LogLevel>()("LogLevel", {
  defaultValue: () => "info" as const
}) {}

v4 Pattern:
import { ServiceMap } from "effect"
const LogLevel = ServiceMap.Reference<"info" | "warn" | "error">("LogLevel", {
  defaultValue: () => "info" as const
})

Reason: Simplified to function syntax, consistent with ServiceMap.Service.

Affected Modules: Context (removed), ServiceMap

Title: Migration: Effect subtyping replaced by Yieldable trait
Category: migration
Source: yieldable.md

Change: In v3, many types (Ref, Deferred, Fiber, FiberRef, Config, Option, Either, Context.Tag) were structural subtypes of Effect. In v4, this is replaced by the Yieldable trait which allows yield* in generators but does NOT make types assignable to Effect.

v3 Pattern:
// Types like Ref, Deferred, Fiber were Effect subtypes
// Could be passed directly to Effect combinators
Effect.map(Option.some(42), (n) => n + 1) // Option is an Effect subtype

v4 Pattern:
interface Yieldable<Self, A, E = never, R = never> {
  asEffect(): Effect<A, E, R>
  [Symbol.iterator](): EffectIterator<Self>
}
// yield* still works in generators
// But must use .asEffect() for Effect combinators
Effect.map(Option.some(42).asEffect(), (n) => n + 1)

Reason: v3 subtyping caused subtle bugs - couldn't distinguish "I have a Ref" from "I have an Effect that reads the Ref." Passing Ref to Effect.map would silently read the value. Yieldable preserves yield* ergonomics while making Effect conversion explicit.

Affected Modules: Effect, Option, Either, Config, ServiceMap

Title: Migration: Ref no longer extends Effect, use Ref.get
Category: migration
Source: yieldable.md

Change: Ref is no longer an Effect subtype and does not implement Yieldable. Use Ref.get(ref) to read the value.

v3 Pattern:
import { Effect, Ref } from "effect"
const program = Effect.gen(function*() {
  const ref = yield* Ref.make(0)
  const value = yield* ref // Ref is an Effect<number>
})

v4 Pattern:
import { Effect, Ref } from "effect"
const program = Effect.gen(function*() {
  const ref = yield* Ref.make(0)
  const value = yield* Ref.get(ref) // Must use Ref.get explicitly
})

Reason: Prevents accidentally treating a Ref as an Effect that reads its value. Makes the read operation explicit.

Affected Modules: Ref

Title: Migration: Deferred no longer extends Effect, use Deferred.await
Category: migration
Source: yieldable.md

Change: Deferred is no longer an Effect subtype and does not implement Yieldable. Use Deferred.await(deferred) to wait for completion.

v3 Pattern:
import { Deferred, Effect } from "effect"
const program = Effect.gen(function*() {
  const deferred = yield* Deferred.make<string, never>()
  const value = yield* deferred // Deferred is an Effect<string>
})

v4 Pattern:
import { Deferred, Effect } from "effect"
const program = Effect.gen(function*() {
  const deferred = yield* Deferred.make<string, never>()
  const value = yield* Deferred.await(deferred) // Must use Deferred.await explicitly
})

Reason: Prevents accidentally awaiting a Deferred when you intended to pass it as a value. Makes the await operation explicit.

Affected Modules: Deferred

Title: Migration: Fiber no longer extends Effect, use Fiber.join
Category: migration
Source: yieldable.md

Change: Fiber is no longer an Effect subtype and does not implement Yieldable. Use Fiber.join(fiber) to await the fiber's result.

v3 Pattern:
import { Effect, Fiber } from "effect"
const program = Effect.gen(function*() {
  const fiber = yield* Effect.fork(task)
  const result = yield* fiber // Fiber is an Effect<A, E>
})

v4 Pattern:
import { Effect, Fiber } from "effect"
const program = Effect.gen(function*() {
  const fiber = yield* Effect.forkChild(task)
  const result = yield* Fiber.join(fiber) // Must use Fiber.join explicitly
})

Reason: Prevents accidentally joining a Fiber when you intended to pass it as a value. Makes the join operation explicit. Note: also uses forkChild instead of fork.

Affected Modules: Fiber, Effect

Title: Migration: Yieldable types require .asEffect() for Effect combinators
Category: migration
Source: yieldable.md

Change: In v4, Yieldable types (Option, Result, Config, etc.) can be used with yield* in generators but must call .asEffect() when passed to Effect combinators like Effect.map, Effect.flatMap, etc.

v3 Pattern:
import { Effect, Option } from "effect"
// Option<number> is assignable to Effect<number, NoSuchElementError>
const program = Effect.map(Option.some(42), (n) => n + 1)

v4 Pattern:
import { Effect, Option } from "effect"
// Option is Yieldable but not Effect - must convert
const program = Effect.map(Option.some(42).asEffect(), (n) => n + 1)
// Or more idiomatically, use a generator:
const program2 = Effect.gen(function*() {
  const n = yield* Option.some(42)
  return n + 1
})

Reason: Explicit conversion prevents subtle bugs where types were silently treated as Effects. Generators are the idiomatic alternative.

Affected Modules: Effect, Option, Result, Config
